suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  library(GenomicRanges)
  library(epiwraps)
  library(ggplot2)
  library(rGREAT)
})

Download the data

#Set timeout options
options(timeout = 6000)
download.file("https://ethz-ins.org/content/w10.assignment.zip", "w10.assignment.zip")
unzip("w10.assignment.zip")
list.files()

Get the regions and the tracks

#Impor the big-wigs for the tracks
tracks <- list.files(pattern="bw$")
#Import the regions in the bed files
peaks <- list.files(pattern="bed$")
# we first import the peaks
peaks <- lapply(peaks, rtracklayer::import.bed)
# we'll focus on the high-quality peaks
peaks <- lapply(peaks, FUN=function(x) x[x$score>800])
# we get the union of non-redundant regions
regions <- reduce(unlist(GRangesList(peaks)))
#Center the signal around the peaks
ml <- signal2Matrix(tracks, regions, extend=2000)
## Reading Creb1.bw
## Reading Creb3.bw
## Reading Creb3L1.bw
#Set the seed and cluster the matrices
set.seed(555)
cl <- clusterSignalMatrices(ml, k=4)
##   ~65% of the variance explained by clusters
#Add the cluster to the peaks
regions$cluster <- cl

#Plot the TFs split by clusters
plotEnrichedHeatmaps(ml, row_split=cl, trim=0.99)

Lets see how many clusters make sense

#iterate over the k values to see which one explains good variance
invisible(lapply(2:10, clusterSignalMatrices, ml = ml))
##   ~37% of the variance explained by clusters
##   ~56% of the variance explained by clusters
##   ~65% of the variance explained by clusters
##   ~72% of the variance explained by clusters
##   ~76% of the variance explained by clusters
##   ~79% of the variance explained by clusters
##   ~81% of the variance explained by clusters
##   ~83% of the variance explained by clusters
##   ~84% of the variance explained by clusters
#Explained variance
variance <- c(37, 56, 64, 72, 76, 79, 81, 83, 84)

plot(x = c(2:10),
     y = variance )

After around 4/5 clusters the amount of explained variance starts to slow down, and thus 4 should be alright. Lets show the figure again.

#Define the colors
mycolors <- c("1"="red", "2"="blue", "3"="darkgreen", "4"="black")
#Plot with the colors
plotEnrichedHeatmaps(ml, row_split=cl, trim=0.99, mean_color = mycolors)

One can see that Creb1 binds in clusters 1, 2 and 4, Creb3 predominantly binds in clusters 2 and 3. while Creb3L1 binds in clusters 2 and 4.

d <- meltSignals(ml, splitBy=cl)
ggplot(d, aes(x = position, y = mean, colour=sample)) + 
  geom_line(linewidth=1.2) + 
  facet_wrap(~split)

Looking at the cluster content, one can see that cluster 3 is mostly bound by Creb3, which is then underrepresented in clusters 1 and 4 where Creb1 and Creb3L1 dominate. Moreover, cluster 2 seems to be around equaly bound by the 3 factors.

Lets check relative signals

#Cluster looking at relative signal
cl_rel <- clusterSignalMatrices(ml, k=4, scaleRows = TRUE)
##   ~86% of the variance explained by clusters
#Melt the signal
d <- meltSignals(ml, splitBy=cl)
#Plot th ecluster means
ggplot(d, aes(position, mean, colour=sample)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  facet_wrap(~split)

#Plot the heatmaps
plotEnrichedHeatmaps(ml, row_split = cl, scale_rows = "global", mean_color = mycolors)

First thing one can see is the larege increase in variance explained, with 86% explained. The clusters show much clearer dominance by factors, with culster 2 being dominated by Creb1, cluster 3 by Creb3 and cluster 4 by Creb3L1. Interestingly cluster 1 is shared by Creb1 and Creb3L1, but contains little to no Creb3. This is recapitulated in the heatmaps.

Lastly we can do a GO enrchment for the clusters

#Split the regions
split_reg <- split(regions, cl_rel)

#Sent the data servers for the clusters
invisible(jobs <- lapply(split_reg, submitGreatJob, bg = regions, species = "hg38"))

Lets look at the top biological processes in all of the clusters

lapply(jobs, FUN = function(x){
  res <- getEnrichmentTables(x)
  bp <- res$`GO Biological Process`
  head(bp)
  
  ggplot(head(bp,15), aes(Hyper_Fold_Enrichment, reorder(name, Hyper_Adjp_BH), size=Hyper_Foreground_Region_Hits, color=-log10(Hyper_Adjp_BH))) +      geom_point() + 
    scale_color_viridis_c()
})

Looking at the results one can see that the first cluster (mostly Cerb1 and Creb3L1) is enriched for developmental functions, not that none of the p-values are significant in this cluster. The second one which is equaly covered by all 3 factors is enriched in signaling and immune response genes. The third one again has no significant hits and contains generally cell cycle, chromatin and RNA management genes. Finally, the 4th cluster contains no significant hits, mostly focusing on metabolic processes, and by the looks of it anabolic ones.
